      <p>
       <i>
        <b>
         Toy Story 3
        </b>
       </i>
       is a  2010 American
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Computer-animated" title="Computer-animated">
        computer-animated
       </a>
       <a href="/wiki/Comedy_film" title="Comedy film">
        comedy film
       </a>
       produced by
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Pixar_Animation_Studios" title="Pixar Animation Studios">
        Pixar Animation Studios
       </a>
       for
       <a href="/wiki/Walt_Disney_Pictures" title="Walt Disney Pictures">
        Walt Disney Pictures
       </a>
       . It is the third installment in the
       <a href="/wiki/Toy_Story_(franchise)" title="Toy Story (franchise)">
        <i>
         Toy Story
        </i>
        franchise
       </a>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-nola-t32_2-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-nola-t32-2">
         [2]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and the sequel to
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Toy_Story_2" title="Toy Story 2">
         Toy Story 2
        </a>
       </i>
       (1999). It was directed by
       <a href="/wiki/Lee_Unkrich" title="Lee Unkrich">
        Lee Unkrich
       </a>
       , the editor of the first two films and the co-director of
       <i>
        Toy Story 2
       </i>
       , written by
       <a href="/wiki/Michael_Arndt" title="Michael Arndt">
        Michael Arndt
       </a>
       , while Unkrich wrote the story along with
       <a href="/wiki/John_Lasseter" title="John Lasseter">
        John Lasseter
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Andrew_Stanton" title="Andrew Stanton">
        Andrew Stanton
       </a>
       , respectively, director and co-writer of the first two films.
      </p>
      <p>
       The plot focuses on
       <a href="/wiki/Sheriff_Woody" title="Sheriff Woody">
        Woody
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Buzz_Lightyear" title="Buzz Lightyear">
        Buzz Lightyear
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_Toy_Story_characters#Andy's_toys" title="List of Toy Story characters">
        Andy's other remaining toys
       </a>
       accidentally being donated to a day care center, while Andy, now 17 years old, is preparing to leave for college, and their ensuing race to get home before Andy leaves. In the film's
       <a href="/wiki/Ensemble_cast" title="Ensemble cast">
        ensemble voice cast
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Tom_Hanks" title="Tom Hanks">
        Tom Hanks
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Tim_Allen" title="Tim Allen">
        Tim Allen
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Joan_Cusack" title="Joan Cusack">
        Joan Cusack
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Don_Rickles" title="Don Rickles">
        Don Rickles
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Wallace_Shawn" title="Wallace Shawn">
        Wallace Shawn
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/John_Ratzenberger" title="John Ratzenberger">
        John Ratzenberger
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Estelle_Harris" title="Estelle Harris">
        Estelle Harris
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Jodi_Benson" title="Jodi Benson">
        Jodi Benson
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/John_Morris_(actor)" title="John Morris (actor)">
        John Morris
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Laurie_Metcalf" title="Laurie Metcalf">
        Laurie Metcalf
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/R._Lee_Ermey" title="R. Lee Ermey">
        R. Lee Ermey
       </a>
       (in his final voice role as Sarge before his death on April 15, 2018), reprise their roles from previous films.
       <a href="/wiki/Jim_Varney" title="Jim Varney">
        Jim Varney
       </a>
       , who voiced Slinky Dog in the first two films, died on February 10, 2000, 10 years before the release of the third film, so the role of Slinky was passed down to
       <a href="/wiki/Blake_Clark" title="Blake Clark">
        Blake Clark
       </a>
       . The returning cast is joined by
       <a href="/wiki/Ned_Beatty" title="Ned Beatty">
        Ned Beatty
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Michael_Keaton" title="Michael Keaton">
        Michael Keaton
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Whoopi_Goldberg" title="Whoopi Goldberg">
        Whoopi Goldberg
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Timothy_Dalton" title="Timothy Dalton">
        Timothy Dalton
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Kristen_Schaal" title="Kristen Schaal">
        Kristen Schaal
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Bonnie_Hunt" title="Bonnie Hunt">
        Bonnie Hunt
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Jeff_Garlin" title="Jeff Garlin">
        Jeff Garlin
       </a>
       who voice the new characters introduced in this film.
      </p>
      <p>
       The film was released in the United States on June 18, 2010.
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       was the first film to be released theatrically with
       <a href="/wiki/Dolby_Surround_7.1" title="Dolby Surround 7.1">
        Dolby Surround 7.1
       </a>
       sound.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-market_watch_3-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-market_watch-3">
         [3]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Like its predecessors,
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       received critical acclaim upon release, with critics praising the vocal performances, screenplay, emotional depth, animation, and
       <a href="/wiki/Randy_Newman" title="Randy Newman">
        Randy Newman
       </a>
       's musical score.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-rt_4-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-rt-4">
         [4]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-mc_5-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-mc-5">
         [5]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       It became the second Pixar film (after
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Up_(2009_film)" title="Up (2009 film)">
         Up
        </a>
       </i>
       ) and third animated film overall (after
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Beauty_and_the_Beast_(1991_film)" title="Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)">
         Beauty and the Beast
        </a>
       </i>
       and
       <i>
        Up
       </i>
       ) to receive an
       <a href="/wiki/Academy_Awards" title="Academy Awards">
        Academy Award
       </a>
       nomination for
       <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Picture" title="Academy Award for Best Picture">
        Best Picture
       </a>
       . The film received four more Academy Award nominations for
       <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Adapted_Screenplay" title="Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay">
        Best Adapted Screenplay
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Sound_Editing" title="Academy Award for Best Sound Editing">
        Best Sound Editing
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Animated_Feature" title="Academy Award for Best Animated Feature">
        Best Animated Feature
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Original_Song" title="Academy Award for Best Original Song">
        Best Original Song
       </a>
       , winning the latter two.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-oscar2_6-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-oscar2-6">
         [6]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       was the first animated film to gross over $1 billion worldwide in ticket sales, becoming the
       <a href="/wiki/2010_in_film#Highest-grossing_films" title="2010 in film">
        highest-grossing film of 2010
       </a>
       both
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/List_of_highest-grossing_films_in_Canada_and_the_United_States" title="List of highest-grossing films in Canada and the United States">
        in North America
       </a>
       and worldwideand the
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_highest-grossing_films" title="List of highest-grossing films">
        fourth-highest-grossing film
       </a>
       at the time of its release, as well as the
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_highest-grossing_animated_films" title="List of highest-grossing animated films">
        highest-grossing animated film of all time
       </a>
       , It is
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_most_expensive_films" title="List of most expensive films">
        one of the most expensive films of all time
       </a>
       and Pixar's highest-grossing film, all records held at the time of its release.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-EWHighestGross2_7-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-EWHighestGross2-7">
         [7]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-onebill2_8-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-onebill2-8">
         [8]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The sequel,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Toy_Story_4" title="Toy Story 4">
         Toy Story 4
        </a>
       </i>
       , was released in June 2019.
      </p>
      <style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r886046785">

      </style>

      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Plot">
        Plot
       </span>
      </h2>
      <p>
       Andy is 17 years old and preparing to leave for college. He has not played with his toys for years, and most have gone, except for
       <a href="/wiki/Sheriff_Woody" title="Sheriff Woody">
        Woody
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Buzz_Lightyear" title="Buzz Lightyear">
        Buzz Lightyear
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Jessie_(Toy_Story)" title="Jessie (Toy Story)">
        Jessie
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Bullseye_(Toy_Story)" title="Bullseye (Toy Story)">
        Bullseye
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Rex_(Toy_Story)" title="Rex (Toy Story)">
        Rex
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Slinky_Dog" title="Slinky Dog">
        Slinky
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Hamm_(Toy_Story)" title="Hamm (Toy Story)">
        Hamm
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Mr._Potato_Head_(Toy_Story)" title="Mr. Potato Head (Toy Story)">
        Mr.
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Mrs._Potato_Head_(Toy_Story)" title="Mrs. Potato Head (Toy Story)">
        Mrs. Potato Head
       </a>
       , the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Squeeze_Toy_Aliens" title="Squeeze Toy Aliens">
        Aliens
       </a>
       , and three
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Sarge_and_the_Bucket_O_Soldiers" title="Sarge and the Bucket O Soldiers">
        toy soldiers
       </a>
       . The despondent toys reflect on their future, and the soldiers parachute out the window and leave.
      </p>
      <p>
       Andy intends to take Woody to college and puts the others into a trash bag to put them in the attic; however, Andy's mother mistakes the bag for trash and puts it on the curb. The toys narrowly escape and, believing Andy threw them away, get into a donation box in his mother's car with Molly's old
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Barbie_(Toy_Story)" title="Barbie (Toy Story)">
        Barbie
       </a>
       doll, bound for Sunnyside Daycare. Woody follows, but is unable to convince them of Andy's real intentions, and goes along when Andy's mother drives to Sunnyside.
      </p>
      <p>
       At Sunnyside, Andy's toys are welcomed by the other toys, led by
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Lots-O%27-Huggin%27_Bear" title="Lots-O'-Huggin' Bear">
        Lots-O'-Huggin' Bear
       </a>
       ("Lotso"). The toys (except Woody) are delighted to learn that Sunnyside never runs out of children, and Barbie is enamored with a
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Ken_(Toy_Story)" title="Ken (Toy Story)">
        Ken
       </a>
       doll.
      </p>
      <p>
       Woody attempts to return home, but is instead found by a child from Sunnyside named Bonnie, who brings him home and plays with him and her other toys. Bonnie's toys are shocked that Woody came from Sunnyside, and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Chuckles_(Toy_Story)" title="Chuckles (Toy Story)">
        Chuckles
       </a>
       , a toy clown, explains that he, Lotso, and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Big_Baby_(Toy_Story)" title="Big Baby (Toy Story)">
        Big Baby
       </a>
       were owned by a girl named Daisy, but were lost during a family trip. When they made it home, Lotso found out that he had been replaced. Embittered, he lied to Big Baby, saying Daisy had replaced all of them. They went to Sunnyside, where Lotso took over, turning it into a toy prison. Chuckles was eventually broken and later found by Bonnie.
      </p>
      <p>
       After Andy's toys are subjected to a very rough playtime with the toddlers, Buzz asks Lotso to move the toys to the older children's room, but Lotso switches Buzz to his original factory setting, erasing his memory. Mrs. Potato Head, through an eye she lost in Andy's room, sees Andy searching for them. They realize that Woody was telling the truth about Andy's intentions and try to leave but, with the assistance of the now brainwashed Buzz, are imprisoned by Lotso's henchmen.
      </p>
      <p>
       Woody returns to Sunnyside, where a
       <a href="/wiki/Chatter_Telephone" title="Chatter Telephone">
        Chatter Telephone
       </a>
       tells him that there is now only one way out the trash. Andy's toys subdue Buzz, but they accidentally reset him to his Spanish mode. Buzz allies himself with Woody and falls in love with Jessie. The toys reach a dumpster but are cornered by Lotso's gang. Woody reveals Lotso's deception to Big Baby, who throws Lotso into the dumpster. As a garbage truck approaches, the toys try to leave, but Lotso pulls Woody into the dumpster. The rest of Andy's toys jump after him, just as the truck arrives, and all fall inside. Buzz returns to normal after a television falls onto him inside the truck.
      </p>
      <p>
       The truck takes the toys to a landfill, where they are swept onto a conveyor belt that leads to an
       <a href="/wiki/Incineration" title="Incineration">
        incinerator
       </a>
       . After narrowly avoiding a
       <a href="/wiki/Industrial_shredder" title="Industrial shredder">
        shredder
       </a>
       , Woody and Buzz help Lotso reach an emergency stop button, only for Lotso to abandon them. The toys fall into the incinerator and resign themselves to their apparent fate, but are rescued at the last second by the Aliens operating the claw crane. Lotso is later found by a garbage truck driver who ties him to his truck's radiator
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Grille_(motor_vehicle)" title="Grille (motor vehicle)">
        grille
       </a>
       . Woody and the other toys ride another garbage truck back to Andy's house.
      </p>
      <p>
       Woody leaves a note for Andy, who, thinking the note is from his mother, donates the toys to Bonnie. Andy introduces the toys individually to Bonnie and, to Andy's surprise, Woody is at the bottom of the donation box, and Bonnie recognizes him. Though initially hesitant, Andy passes Woody on to Bonnie, and they play together before he leaves. Woody and the other toys witness Andy's departure as they begin their new lives with Bonnie.
      </p>
      <p>
       In the film's epilogue, Barbie, Ken, and Big Baby have made vast improvements to Sunnyside and maintain contact with Bonnie's toys through letters. The toy soldiers parachute into Sunnyside, and they are welcomed in by Ken and Barbie.
      </p>

         </a>

        </li>

        </li>
       </ul>
      </div>
      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Production">
        Production
       </span>
      </h2>
      <p>
       According to the terms of Pixar's initial seven-film deal with
       <a href="/wiki/The_Walt_Disney_Company" title="The Walt Disney Company">
        Disney
       </a>
       , all characters created by Pixar for their films were owned by Disney.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-CBSNewsAdios_14-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-CBSNewsAdios-14">
         [14]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Furthermore, Disney retained the rights to make sequels to any Pixar film,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-CBSNewsAdios_14-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-CBSNewsAdios-14">
         [14]
        </a>
       </sup>
       though Pixar retained the
       <a href="/wiki/Right_of_first_refusal" title="Right of first refusal">
        right of first refusal
       </a>
       to work on these sequels.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-15">
        <a href="#cite_note-15">
         [15]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In 2004, when the contentious negotiations between the two companies made a split appear likely,
       <a href="/wiki/Michael_Eisner" title="Michael Eisner">
        Michael Eisner
       </a>
       , Disney chairman at the time, put plans in motion to produce
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       at a new Disney studio,
       <a href="/wiki/Circle_7_Animation" title="Circle 7 Animation">
        Circle 7 Animation
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-untold_16-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-untold-16">
         [16]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Tim Allen, the voice of Buzz Lightyear, indicated a willingness to return, even if Pixar was not on board. It was slated for a theatrical release sometime in Spring 2008.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-17">
        <a href="#cite_note-17">
         [17]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:242px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:ToyStory3PromoImage.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="258" data-file-width="387" decoding="async" height="160" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/54/ToyStory3PromoImage.jpg/240px-ToyStory3PromoImage.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/5/54/ToyStory3PromoImage.jpg/360px-ToyStory3PromoImage.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/5/54/ToyStory3PromoImage.jpg 2x" width="240"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:ToyStory3PromoImage.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         Promotional art for
         <a href="/wiki/Circle_7_Animation" title="Circle 7 Animation">
          Circle 7
         </a>
         's
         <i>
          Toy Story 3
         </i>
         at Siggraph 2005, displaying the storyline of the
         <a href="/wiki/Product_recall" title="Product recall">
          recalled
         </a>
         Buzz Lightyears.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Bradley_Raymond" title="Bradley Raymond">
        Bradley Raymond
       </a>
       who previously directed Disney's direct-to-video sequels such as
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Hunchback_of_Notre_Dame_II" title="The Hunchback of Notre Dame II">
         The Hunchback of Notre Dame II
        </a>
       </i>
       , and
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Lion_King_1%C2%BD" title="The Lion King 1">
         The Lion King 1
        </a>
       </i>
       was hired to direct the film. Among the scripts Circle 7 had under consideration was one from
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Teacher%27s_Pet_(2004_film)" title="Teacher's Pet (2004 film)">
         Teacher's Pet
        </a>
       </i>
       screenwriters
       <a href="/wiki/Bill_and_Cheri_Steinkellner" title="Bill and Cheri Steinkellner">
        Bill and Cheri Steinkellner
       </a>
       . Their idea for the film involves Andy and his toys (Woody, Buzz, Hamm, Rex, Slinky, Mr. Potato Head, Jessie, and Bullseye) paying a visit to his grandmother's house for the night, because his room is getting remodeled. So a set of Andy's toys and new characters Hee-Hee, and Gladiola are trying to figure out who stole the toys one by one in a whodunit-style murder mystery story.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-18">
        <a href="#cite_note-18">
         [18]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TS3Script_19-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-TS3Script-19">
         [19]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Though it was rejected, Disney was so impressed with the script that this version would have been considered for a possible fourth installment.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-20">
        <a href="#cite_note-20">
         [20]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The final version of the Circle 7 script was written by
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Meet_the_Parents" title="Meet the Parents">
         Meet the Parents
        </a>
       </i>
       screenwriter
       <a href="/wiki/Jim_Herzfeld" title="Jim Herzfeld">
        Jim Herzfeld
       </a>
       . It focused on Andy's toys shipping a malfunctioning Buzz to the factory in
       <a href="/wiki/Taiwan" title="Taiwan">
        Taiwan
       </a>
       where he was built called Wocka-Wocka, with the other toys hoping he will be fixed there. While searching on the Internet, they then discovered that many more Buzz Lightyear toys are malfunctioning around the world and the company had issued a massive
       <a href="/wiki/Product_recall" title="Product recall">
        recall
       </a>
       . Fearing Buzz's destruction, a group of Andy's toys (Woody, Rex, Slinky, Mr. Potato Head, Hamm, Jessie, and Bullseye) all ship themselves to Taiwan and venture out to rescue Buzz. At the same time, Buzz meets other toys from around the world that were once loved, but have been recalled such as Rosey, a warm cozy toy and Jade, a leggy doll with an evening gown. Along with meeting the recalled toys, Buzz also meet a new Star Command action figure that was going to be the replacement of Buzz, Daxx Blastar, along with his accessory pet cat named Comet.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-untold_16-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-untold-16">
         [16]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TS3Script_19-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-TS3Script-19">
         [19]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       In January 2006,
       <a href="/wiki/Pixar#Disney_subsidiary" title="Pixar">
        Disney bought Pixar
       </a>
       in a deal that put Pixar chiefs
       <a href="/wiki/Edwin_Catmull" title="Edwin Catmull">
        Edwin Catmull
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/John_Lasseter" title="John Lasseter">
        John Lasseter
       </a>
       in charge of all Disney Animation.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-21">
        <a href="#cite_note-21">
         [21]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Shortly thereafter, led Circle 7 Animation was shut down and its alternate version of
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       was canceled.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-untold_16-2">
        <a href="#cite_note-untold-16">
         [16]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" style="white-space:nowrap;">
        :
        <span>
         1
        </span>
       </sup>
       The following month, Disney CEO
       <a href="/wiki/Bob_Iger" title="Bob Iger">
        Robert Iger
       </a>
       confirmed that Disney was in the process of transferring the production to Pixar.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-22">
        <a href="#cite_note-22">
         [22]
        </a>
       </sup>
       John Lasseter,
       <a href="/wiki/Andrew_Stanton" title="Andrew Stanton">
        Andrew Stanton
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Pete_Docter" title="Pete Docter">
        Pete Docter
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/Lee_Unkrich" title="Lee Unkrich">
        Lee Unkrich
       </a>
       visited the house where they first pitched
       <i>
        Toy Story
       </i>
       and came up with the story for the film over a weekend. Stanton then wrote a
       <a href="/wiki/Film_treatment" title="Film treatment">
        treatment
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-pr_23-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-pr-23">
         [23]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       This story had no traces of the Circle 7 version of the film, since the filmmakers did not read its script: "Not out of spite, but we wanted to start fresh, and not be influenced by what they'd done," said Unkrich. "We didn't look at any of the work they'd done. We really didn't want to know anything about it."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-EWHappyEnding_24-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-EWHappyEnding-24">
         [24]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In February 2007, Lasseter announced
       <i>
        Toy Story 2
       </i>
       <span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">
        '
       </span>
       s co-director, Unkrich, as the sole director of the film instead of himself (Lasseter had directed the first two films and was busy directing
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Cars_2" title="Cars 2">
         Cars 2
        </a>
       </i>
       ), and
       <a href="/wiki/Michael_Arndt" title="Michael Arndt">
        Michael Arndt
       </a>
       as screenwriter.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-25">
        <a href="#cite_note-25">
         [25]
        </a>
       </sup>
       2010 was also announced as the tentative release date.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-EWHappyEnding_24-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-EWHappyEnding-24">
         [24]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Unkrich, who had been working with Arndt and story development artists on the film since the middle of 2006,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-EWHappyEnding_24-2">
        <a href="#cite_note-EWHappyEnding-24">
         [24]
        </a>
       </sup>
       said that he felt pressure to avoid creating "the first dud" for Pixar, since (as of 2010) all of Pixar's films had been critical and commercial successes.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-26">
        <a href="#cite_note-26">
         [26]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In February 2008, the film's plotline was reported: "Woody the cowboy and his toy box friends are dumped in a daycare centre after their owner, Andy, leaves for college."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-wsj_27-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-wsj-27">
         [27]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Lee_Unkrich_at_WonderCon_2010_3.JPG">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2736" data-file-width="3648" decoding="async" height="165" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Lee_Unkrich_at_WonderCon_2010_3.JPG/220px-Lee_Unkrich_at_WonderCon_2010_3.JPG" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Lee_Unkrich_at_WonderCon_2010_3.JPG/330px-Lee_Unkrich_at_WonderCon_2010_3.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Lee_Unkrich_at_WonderCon_2010_3.JPG/440px-Lee_Unkrich_at_WonderCon_2010_3.JPG 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Lee_Unkrich_at_WonderCon_2010_3.JPG" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <a href="/wiki/Lee_Unkrich" title="Lee Unkrich">
          Lee Unkrich
         </a>
         , pictured at the
         <i>
          Toy Story 3
         </i>
         panel at WonderCon in April 2010, was the full-time director for the film.
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       During the initial development stages of the film, Pixar revisited their work from the original
       <i>
        Toy Story
       </i>
       and found that, although they could open the old
       <a href="/wiki/Computer_file" title="Computer file">
        computer files
       </a>
       for the animated
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/3D_model" title="3D model">
        3D models
       </a>
       , error messages prevented them from editing the files. This necessitated recreating the models from scratch.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-28">
        <a href="#cite_note-28">
         [28]
        </a>
       </sup>
       To create the chaotic and complex junkyard scene near the film's end, more than a year and a half was invested on research and development to create the simulation systems required for the sequence.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-29">
        <a href="#cite_note-29">
         [29]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Instead of sending Tom Hanks, Tim Allen and John Ratzenberger scripts for their consideration in reprising their roles, a complete story reel of the film was shown to the actors in a theater. The reel was made up of moving storyboards with pre-recorded voices, sound effects, and music. At the conclusion of the preview, the actors signed on to the film.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-empire_online_30-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-empire_online-30">
         [30]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The film's art director is
       <a href="/wiki/Daisuke_Tsutsumi" title="Daisuke Tsutsumi">
        Daisuke Tsutsumi
       </a>
       . He is married to
       <a href="/wiki/Hayao_Miyazaki" title="Hayao Miyazaki">
        Hayao Miyazaki
       </a>
       's niece, who was the original inspiration for the character Mei in Miyazaki's
       <a href="/wiki/Anime" title="Anime">
        anime
       </a>
       film
       <i>
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/My_Neighbour_Totoro" title="My Neighbour Totoro">
         My Neighbour Totoro
        </a>
       </i>
       (1988). Totoro makes a cameo appearance in
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Niece_31-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Niece-31">
         [31]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Dolby_Laboratories" title="Dolby Laboratories">
        Dolby Laboratories
       </a>
       announced that
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       would be the first film to feature theatrical
       <a href="/wiki/7.1_surround_sound" title="7.1 surround sound">
        7.1 surround sound
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-market_watch_3-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-market_watch-3">
         [3]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Thus, even the
       <a href="/wiki/Blu-ray" title="Blu-ray">
        Blu-ray
       </a>
       version would feature original 7.1 audio, unlike other films which were remixed into 7.1 for Blu-ray.
      </p>
      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Release">
        Release
       </span>
      </h2>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Theatrical">
        Theatrical
       </span>
      </h3>
      <div class="thumb tleft">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Toy_Story_3,_El_Capitan_Theatre,_2010.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="2856" data-file-width="3570" decoding="async" height="176" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Toy_Story_3%2C_El_Capitan_Theatre%2C_2010.jpg/220px-Toy_Story_3%2C_El_Capitan_Theatre%2C_2010.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Toy_Story_3%2C_El_Capitan_Theatre%2C_2010.jpg/330px-Toy_Story_3%2C_El_Capitan_Theatre%2C_2010.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/db/Toy_Story_3%2C_El_Capitan_Theatre%2C_2010.jpg/440px-Toy_Story_3%2C_El_Capitan_Theatre%2C_2010.jpg 2x" width="220"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Toy_Story_3,_El_Capitan_Theatre,_2010.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <i>
          Toy Story 3
         </i>
         had its United States premiere at
         <a href="/wiki/El_Capitan_Theatre" title="El Capitan Theatre">
          El Capitan Theatre
         </a>
         ,
         <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ReutersPremiere_32-0">
          <a href="#cite_note-ReutersPremiere-32">
           [32]
          </a>
         </sup>
         which also hosted a
         <i>
          Toy Story
         </i>
         marathon showing all three films together for the first time.
         <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-BWTakesOver_33-0">
          <a href="#cite_note-BWTakesOver-33">
           [33]
          </a>
         </sup>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       had its worldwide premiere on June 12, 2010, opening at
       <a href="/wiki/Taormina_Film_Fest" title="Taormina Film Fest">
        Taormina Film Fest
       </a>
       in Italy.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-34">
        <a href="#cite_note-34">
         [34]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In the United States, it premiered on June 13, 2010, at
       <a href="/wiki/El_Capitan_Theatre" title="El Capitan Theatre">
        El Capitan Theatre
       </a>
       in Hollywood, California.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-ReutersPremiere_32-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-ReutersPremiere-32">
         [32]
        </a>
       </sup>
       El Capitan also hosted on June 17, 2010, a
       <i>
        Toy Story
       </i>
       marathon, showing for the first time all three
       <i>
        Toy Story
       </i>
       films together.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-BWTakesOver_33-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-BWTakesOver-33">
         [33]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The film went into its wide release on June 18, 2010, along with a release to
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/IMAX_3D" title="IMAX 3D">
        IMAX 3D
       </a>
       theaters.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-35">
        <a href="#cite_note-35">
         [35]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The film was theatrically accompanied with the Pixar short film
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Day_%26_Night_(2010_film)" title="Day &amp; Night (2010 film)">
         Day &amp; Night
        </a>
       </i>
       , which focuses on what happens when an animated personification of
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Daytime_(astronomy)" title="Daytime (astronomy)">
        Day
       </a>
       meets his opposite, Night, and the resulting growth for both.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-36">
        <a href="#cite_note-36">
         [36]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-37">
        <a href="#cite_note-37">
         [37]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Marketing">
        Marketing
       </span>
      </h3>
      <p>
       The film's first
       <a href="/wiki/Teaser_campaign" title="Teaser campaign">
        teaser trailer
       </a>
       was released with
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Up_(2009_film)" title="Up (2009 film)">
         Up
        </a>
       </i>
       in
       <a href="/wiki/Disney_Digital_3-D" title="Disney Digital 3-D">
        Disney Digital 3-D
       </a>
       on May 29, 2009.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-38">
        <a href="#cite_note-38">
         [38]
        </a>
       </sup>
       On October 2, 2009,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Toy_Story" title="Toy Story">
         Toy Story
        </a>
       </i>
       and
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Toy_Story_2" title="Toy Story 2">
         Toy Story 2
        </a>
       </i>
       were re-released as a double feature in Disney Digital 3-D.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-releasedate_39-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-releasedate-39">
         [39]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The first full-length
       <a href="/wiki/Trailer_(promotion)" title="Trailer (promotion)">
        trailer
       </a>
       was attached as an exclusive sneak peek and a first footage to the
       <i>
        Toy Story
       </i>
       double feature on October 12, 2009.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-40">
        <a href="#cite_note-40">
         [40]
        </a>
       </sup>
       A second teaser was released on February 10, 2010, followed by a second full-length trailer on February 11, and appeared in 3D showings of
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Alice_in_Wonderland_(2010_film)" title="Alice in Wonderland (2010 film)">
         Alice in Wonderland
        </a>
       </i>
       and
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/How_to_Train_Your_Dragon_(film)" title="How to Train Your Dragon (film)">
         How to Train Your Dragon
        </a>
       </i>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-41">
        <a href="#cite_note-41">
         [41]
        </a>
       </sup>
       On March 23, 2010,
       <i>
        Toy Story
       </i>
       and
       <i>
        Toy Story 2
       </i>
       were released separately on Blu-ray/DVD combo packs;
       <i>
        Toy Story
       </i>
       included a small feature of "The Story of
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       " and
       <i>
        Toy Story 2
       </i>
       included one on the "Characters of
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       ."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-42">
        <a href="#cite_note-42">
         [42]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-43">
        <a href="#cite_note-43">
         [43]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>

        </a>

         </a>
         , who voiced Jessie in the film, signing
         <i>

         </i>
         merchandise.

       </a>
       , Thinkway Toys, and

       </a>
       , a Mattel Company, released
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       with 21 3D images for viewing with the
       <a href="/wiki/View-Master" title="View-Master">
        View-Master
       </a>
       viewer.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-44">
        <a href="#cite_note-44">
         [44]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-45">
        <a href="#cite_note-45">
         [45]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Disney_Interactive_Studios" title="Disney Interactive Studios">
        Disney Interactive Studios
       </a>
       also produced a video game based on the film
       <i>
        <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Toy_Story_3:_The_Video_Game" title="Toy Story 3: The Video Game">
         Toy Story 3: The Video Game
        </a>
       </i>
       , which was released for
       <a href="/wiki/Microsoft_Windows" title="Microsoft Windows">
        Microsoft Windows
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Xbox_360" title="Xbox 360">
        Xbox 360
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Wii" title="Wii">
        Wii
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/PlayStation_3" title="PlayStation 3">
        PlayStation 3
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Nintendo_DS" title="Nintendo DS">
        Nintendo DS
       </a>
       , and
       <a href="/wiki/PlayStation_Portable" title="PlayStation Portable">
        PSP
       </a>
       on June 15, 2010.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-46">
        <a href="#cite_note-46">
         [46]
        </a>
       </sup>
       A
       <a href="/wiki/PlayStation_2" title="PlayStation 2">
        PlayStation 2
       </a>
       version was released on October 30, 2010 as part of a PS2 bundle and separately on November 2, 2010 (the same day
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       was released on DVD and Blu-ray).
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-amazon1_47-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-amazon1-47">
         [47]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It was also the last Disney/Pixar game to be released for PlayStation 2.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-amazon1_47-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-amazon1-47">
         [47]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       was featured in Apple's iPhone
       <a href="/wiki/IOS_4" title="IOS 4">
        OS 4
       </a>
       Event on April 8, 2010, with
       <a href="/wiki/Steve_Jobs" title="Steve Jobs">
        Steve Jobs
       </a>
       demonstrating a
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       -themed
       <a href="/wiki/IAd" title="IAd">
        iAd
       </a>
       written in
       <a href="/wiki/HTML5" title="HTML5">
        HTML5
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-48">
        <a href="#cite_note-48">
         [48]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Pixar designed a commercial for the toy
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_Toy_Story_characters#Lots-O'-Huggin'_Bear" title="List of Toy Story characters">
        Lots-O'-Huggin' Bear
       </a>
       and formatted it to appear as if it came from an old VCR recording. The recording was altered with distorted sound, noise along the bottom of the screen, and flickering video, all designed to make it look like a converted recording from around 1983.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-49">
        <a href="#cite_note-49">
         [49]
        </a>
       </sup>
       A Japanese version of the commercial was also released online, with the name "Lots-O'-Huggin Bear" replaced with "Little Hug-Hug Bear" (Japanese:/
       <i>
        Hagu Hagu Beya-Chan
       </i>
       ).
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-50">
        <a href="#cite_note-50">
         [50]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       On
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Dancing_with_the_Stars_(American_season_10)" title="Dancing with the Stars (American season 10)">
         Dancing with the Stars
        </a>
       </i>
       <span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">
        '
       </span>

       <a href="/wiki/Gipsy_Kings" title="Gipsy Kings">

       </a>

       <a href="/wiki/You%27ve_Got_a_Friend_in_Me" title="You've Got a Friend in Me">
        You've Got a Friend in Me
       </a>
       ," which featured a
       <a href="/wiki/Pasodoble" title="Pasodoble">
        paso doble
       </a>
       dance choreographed by
       <a href="/wiki/Cheryl_Burke" title="Cheryl Burke">
        Cheryl Burke
       </a>
       and
       <a href="/wiki/Tony_Dovolani" title="Tony Dovolani">
        Tony Dovolani
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-51">
        <a href="#cite_note-51">
         [51]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-52">
        <a href="#cite_note-52">
         [52]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Both the song and dance are featured in the film.
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>

       <a href="/wiki/Disney_Channel" title="Disney Channel">

       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-53">

        ABC Family

        <a href="#cite_note-WrapABCFirstLook-55">
         [55]
        </a>
       </sup>

       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>

       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-WrapABCFirstLook_55-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-WrapABCFirstLook-55">
         [55]

       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-56">
        <a href="#cite_note-56">
