      <h4>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Oscar_campaign">
        Oscar campaign
       </span>
      </h4>
      <p>
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       <span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">
        '
       </span>
       s "Not since..." Oscar campaign drew a lot of attention, emphasizing the film's uniqueness and critical acclaim. The campaign consisted of posters featuring characters from the film, comparing
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       to previous winners such as
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Lord_of_the_Rings:_The_Return_of_the_King" title="The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King">
         The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare_in_Love" title="Shakespeare in Love">
         Shakespeare in Love
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Titanic_(1997_film)" title="Titanic (1997 film)">
         Titanic
        </a>
       </i>
       , and more.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-58">
        <a href="#cite_note-58">
         [58]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Walt_Disney_Studios_(division)" title="Walt Disney Studios (division)">
        Walt Disney Studios
       </a>
       Chairman
       <a href="/wiki/Rich_Ross" title="Rich Ross">
        Rich Ross
       </a>
       explained they were going for the Best Picture win, not just Best Animated film.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-59">
        <a href="#cite_note-59">
         [59]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Hollywood_Reporter" title="The Hollywood Reporter">
         The Hollywood Reporter
        </a>
       </i>
       gave the campaign a bronze award in Key Art Awards Winners 2011.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-60">
        <a href="#cite_note-60">
         [60]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Home_media">
        Home media
       </span>
      </h3>
      <p>
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       was released by
       <a href="/wiki/Walt_Disney_Studios_Home_Entertainment" title="Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment">
        Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment
       </a>
       in North America on November 2, 2010, in a standard DVD edition, a two-disc
       <a href="/wiki/Blu-ray" title="Blu-ray">
        Blu-ray
       </a>
       Disc, and in a four-disc Blu-ray/DVD/Digital Copy combo pack. Features included behind-the-scenes, including a sneak peek teaser for the then-upcoming
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Cars_2" title="Cars 2">
         Cars 2
        </a>
       </i>
       (the sequel to the 2006 film
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Cars_(film)" title="Cars (film)">
         Cars
        </a>
       </i>
       ).
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-61">
        <a href="#cite_note-61">
         [61]
        </a>
       </sup>
       A 10-disc
       <i>
        Toy Story
       </i>
       trilogy Blu-ray box set arrived on store shelves that same day.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-62">
        <a href="#cite_note-62">
         [62]
        </a>
       </sup>
       A
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_Blu-ray_3D_releases" title="List of Blu-ray 3D releases">
        3D version of the Blu-ray
       </a>
       was released in North America on November 1, 2011.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-63">
        <a href="#cite_note-63">
         [63]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       On its first week of release (November 27, 2010), it sold 3,859,736 units (equal to $73,096,452), ranking No.1 for the week and immediately becoming the bestselling animated film of 2010 in units sold (surpassing
       <i>
        How to Train Your Dragon
       </i>
       ). As of July 18, 2012, it had sold 10,911,701 units ($185,924,247).
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-64">
        <a href="#cite_note-64">
         [64]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It became the bestselling DVD of 2010 in units sold, but it lacked in sales revenue and therefore ranked second behind
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Avatar_(2009_film)#Home_media" title="Avatar (2009 film)">
         Avatar
        </a>
       </i>
       on that list.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-65">
        <a href="#cite_note-65">
         [65]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It also sold about 4 million Blu-ray units, ranking as the fourth-bestselling film of 2010.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-66">
        <a href="#cite_note-66">
         [66]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       In the
       <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">
        United Kingdom
       </a>
       , it broke the record for the largest first day ever for an animated feature in sales revenue, on both DVD and Blu-ray. Additionally, on the first day of its
       <a href="/wiki/ITunes" title="ITunes">
        iTunes
       </a>
       release, it immediately became the most downloaded Disney film ever.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-67">
        <a href="#cite_note-67">
         [67]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       was released on
       <a href="/wiki/Ultra_HD_Blu-ray" title="Ultra HD Blu-ray">
        4K UHD Blu-ray
       </a>
       on June 4, 2019.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-68">
        <a href="#cite_note-68">
         [68]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       The film was released on
       <a href="/wiki/Disney%2B" title="Disney+">
        Disney+
       </a>
       on November 12, 2019.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-69">
        <a href="#cite_note-69">
         [69]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Reception">
        Reception
       </span>
      </h2>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Box_office">
        Box office
       </span>
      </h3>
      <p>
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       earned $415million in North America and $652million in other countries for a worldwide total of $1.067billion, earning more revenue than the previous two films of the series combined.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-mojo1_1-3">
        <a href="#cite_note-mojo1-1">
         [1]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It became the
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_highest-grossing_animated_films" title="List of highest-grossing animated films">
        highest-grossing animated film
       </a>
       , surpassing the six-year-old record held by 2004's
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Shrek_2" title="Shrek 2">
         Shrek 2
        </a>
       </i>
       ($919million),
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-EWHighestGross2_7-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-EWHighestGross2-7">
         [7]
        </a>
       </sup>
       until
       <a href="/wiki/Walt_Disney_Animation_Studios" title="Walt Disney Animation Studios">
        Walt Disney Animation Studios
       </a>
       ' computer-animated musical
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Frozen_(2013_film)" title="Frozen (2013 film)">
         Frozen
        </a>
       </i>
       surpassed it in 2014, followed by
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Minions_(film)" title="Minions (film)">
         Minions
        </a>
       </i>
       in 2015,
       <i>
        Incredibles 2
       </i>
       in 2018, and computer-animated remake version of
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Lion_King_(2019_film)" title="The Lion King (2019 film)">
         The Lion King
        </a>
       </i>
       , its sequel
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Toy_Story_4" title="Toy Story 4">
         Toy Story 4
        </a>
       </i>
       and
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Frozen_II" title="Frozen II">
         Frozen II
        </a>
       </i>
       in 2019.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-TimeFrozenTop_70-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-TimeFrozenTop-70">
         [70]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It is the
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_highest-grossing_films" title="List of highest-grossing films">
        34th-highest-grossing film
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-mojo-alltime_71-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-mojo-alltime-71">
         [71]
        </a>
       </sup>
       the
       <a href="/wiki/2010_in_film" title="2010 in film">
        highest-grossing film of 2010
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-72">
        <a href="#cite_note-72">
         [72]
        </a>
       </sup>
       the seventh-highest-grossing animated film (behind 2019 CGI version of
       <i>
        The Lion King
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        Frozen II
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        Frozen
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        Incredibles 2
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        Minions
       </i>
       and
       <i>
        Toy Story 4
       </i>
       ),
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-onebill2_8-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-onebill2-8">
         [8]
        </a>
       </sup>
       the second highest-grossing film in the
       <a href="/wiki/Toy_Story_(franchise)" title="Toy Story (franchise)">
        <i>
         Toy Story
        </i>
        series
       </a>
       (behind
       <i>
        Toy Story 4
       </i>
       ),
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-73">
        <a href="#cite_note-73">
         [73]
        </a>
       </sup>
       the third-highest-grossing Pixar film (behind
       <i>
        Incredibles 2
       </i>
       and
       <i>
        Toy Story 4
       </i>
       ),
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Pixar_Movies_at_the_Box_Office_74-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Pixar_Movies_at_the_Box_Office-74">
         [74]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and the 18th-highest-grossing film distributed by
       <a href="/wiki/Walt_Disney_Studios_Motion_Pictures" title="Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures">
        Disney
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-75">
        <a href="#cite_note-75">
         [75]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In estimated attendance, though, it still ranks fourth on the list of modern animated films, behind
       <i>
        Shrek 2
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Finding_Nemo" title="Finding Nemo">
         Finding Nemo
        </a>
       </i>
       , and
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Lion_King" title="The Lion King">
         The Lion King
        </a>
       </i>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-onebill2_8-2">
        <a href="#cite_note-onebill2-8">
         [8]
        </a>
       </sup>
       On its first weekend,
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       topped the worldwide box office with $145.3million ($153.7million with weekday previews), the
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_highest-grossing_openings_for_animated_films" title="List of highest-grossing openings for animated films">
        ninth-largest opening weekend worldwide for an animated feature
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-76">
        <a href="#cite_note-76">
         [76]
        </a>
       </sup>
       On August 27, 2010  its seventy-first day of release, it surpassed the $1billion mark, becoming the third Disney film, the second Disney-distributed film in 2010 (after
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Alice_in_Wonderland_(2010_film)" title="Alice in Wonderland (2010 film)">
         Alice in Wonderland
        </a>
       </i>
       ), the first animated film,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-onebill2_8-3">
        <a href="#cite_note-onebill2-8">
         [8]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and the seventh film in cinematic history to do so.
      </p>
      <h4>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="United_States_and_Canada">
        United States and Canada
       </span>
      </h4>
      <p>
       In North America,
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       is the
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/List_of_highest-grossing_films_in_Canada_and_the_United_States" title="List of highest-grossing films in Canada and the United States">
        19th-highest-grossing film
       </a>
       , unadjusted for inflation. Adjusted for ticket price inflation, though, it ranks 96th on the all-time chart.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-77">
        <a href="#cite_note-77">
         [77]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It is also the highest-grossing film of 2010,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-78">
        <a href="#cite_note-78">
         [78]
        </a>
       </sup>
       the second-highest-grossing Pixar film (behind
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Finding_Dory" title="Finding Dory">
         Finding Dory
        </a>
       </i>
       ),
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Pixar_Movies_at_the_Box_Office_74-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-Pixar_Movies_at_the_Box_Office-74">
         [74]
        </a>
       </sup>
       the second-highest-grossing G-rated film (behind
       <i>
        The Lion King
       </i>
       ),
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-79">
        <a href="#cite_note-79">
         [79]
        </a>
       </sup>
       the fourth-highest-grossing animated film,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-80">
        <a href="#cite_note-80">
         [80]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and the seventh-highest-grossing film distributed by Disney.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-81">
        <a href="#cite_note-81">
         [81]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Box_Office_Mojo" title="Box Office Mojo">
        Box Office Mojo
       </a>
       estimates that the film sold over 52 million tickets in the U.S.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-82">
        <a href="#cite_note-82">
         [82]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The film earned $41.1million on its opening day (June 18, 2010) from 4,028 theaters, including $4million at midnight shows from about 1,500 theaters, setting an opening-day record for an animated film
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-83">
        <a href="#cite_note-83">
         [83]
        </a>
       </sup>
       (surpassed by
       <i>
        Minions
       </i>
       and later
       <i>
        Finding Dory
       </i>
       ).
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-84">
        <a href="#cite_note-84">
         [84]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-85">
        <a href="#cite_note-85">
         [85]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       During its opening weekend, the film topped the box office with $110.3million, setting an opening-weekend record among Pixar films
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-86">
        <a href="#cite_note-86">
         [86]
        </a>
       </sup>
       (surpassed by
       <i>
        Finding Dory
       </i>
       ),
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-87">
        <a href="#cite_note-87">
         [87]
        </a>
       </sup>
       films released in June
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-openingjune_88-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-openingjune-88">
         [88]
        </a>
       </sup>
       (surpassed by
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Man_of_Steel_(film)" title="Man of Steel (film)">
         Man of Steel
        </a>
       </i>
       and later
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Jurassic_World" title="Jurassic World">
         Jurassic World
        </a>
       </i>
       ),
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-89">
        <a href="#cite_note-89">
         [89]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-90">
        <a href="#cite_note-90">
         [90]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and G-rated films.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-91">
        <a href="#cite_note-91">
         [91]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The film also achieved the second-largest opening weekend among animated films
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-92">
        <a href="#cite_note-92">
         [92]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and the fourth-largest opening weekend among 2010 films.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-93">
        <a href="#cite_note-93">
         [93]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Its average of $27,385 per venue is the second-highest for a G-rated film and the third-highest for an animated feature.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-94">
        <a href="#cite_note-94">
         [94]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Its opening-week gross (Friday through Thursday) of $167.6million is the second-largest among animated films, the second-largest among 2010 films, and the 23rd-largest of all time.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-95">
        <a href="#cite_note-95">
         [95]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It also achieved the largest 10-day gross among 2010 films.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-96">
        <a href="#cite_note-96">
         [96]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It topped the box office for two consecutive weekends.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-97">
        <a href="#cite_note-97">
         [97]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h4>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Other_territories">
        Other territories
       </span>
      </h4>
      <p>
       Outside of North America,
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       is the 29th-highest-grossing film,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-overseas_98-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-overseas-98">
         [98]
        </a>
       </sup>
       the sixth-highest-grossing animated film, the third-highest-grossing film of 2010,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-99">
        <a href="#cite_note-99">
         [99]
        </a>
       </sup>
       the highest-grossing Pixar film, and the 11th-highest-grossing Disney film.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-overseas_98-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-overseas-98">
         [98]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It topped the box office outside North America three times, in its first ($35million),
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-100">
        <a href="#cite_note-100">
         [100]
        </a>
       </sup>
       second,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-101">
        <a href="#cite_note-101">
         [101]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and sixth weekend (which was its largest).
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-102">
        <a href="#cite_note-102">
         [102]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       Its highest-grossing market after North America is Japan ($126.7million),
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-103">
        <a href="#cite_note-103">
         [103]
        </a>
       </sup>
       where it is the second-highest-grossing U.S. animated feature (behind
       <i>
        Finding Nemo
       </i>
       ),
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-onebill2_8-4">
        <a href="#cite_note-onebill2-8">
         [8]
        </a>
       </sup>
       followed by the UK and Ireland, and Malta (73.8million  $116.6million), where it is the
       <a href="/wiki/List_of_highest-grossing_films_in_the_United_Kingdom" title="List of highest-grossing films in the United Kingdom">
        sixth-highest-grossing film
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-104">
        <a href="#cite_note-104">
         [104]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and Mexico ($59.4million), where it is the second-highest-grossing film.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Mexico_105-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Mexico-105">
         [105]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It set opening-weekend records for animated films in Ecuador, Colombia, Mexico, China, Argentina,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-106">
        <a href="#cite_note-106">
         [106]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Hong Kong,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-107">
        <a href="#cite_note-107">
         [107]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Spain, and the UK.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-108">
        <a href="#cite_note-108">
         [108]
        </a>
       </sup>
       It is the highest-grossing animated film of all time in the UK, Ireland and Malta,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-109">
        <a href="#cite_note-109">
         [109]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-110">
        <a href="#cite_note-110">
         [110]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Mexico,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Mexico_105-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-Mexico-105">
         [105]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Hong Kong,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-111">
        <a href="#cite_note-111">
         [111]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-112">
        <a href="#cite_note-112">
         [112]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and Egypt. It is the highest-grossing film of 2010 in Argentina,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-113">
        <a href="#cite_note-113">
         [113]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Bolivia,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-114">
        <a href="#cite_note-114">
         [114]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Chile,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-115">
        <a href="#cite_note-115">
         [115]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Colombia,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-116">
        <a href="#cite_note-116">
         [116]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Hong Kong,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-117">
        <a href="#cite_note-117">
         [117]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Mexico,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-118">
        <a href="#cite_note-118">
         [118]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Spain,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-119">
        <a href="#cite_note-119">
         [119]
        </a>
       </sup>
       the UK, Ireland, and Malta.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-120">
        <a href="#cite_note-120">
         [120]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Critical_response">
        Critical response
       </span>
      </h3>
      <p>
       On review aggregation website
       <a href="/wiki/Rotten_Tomatoes" title="Rotten Tomatoes">
        Rotten Tomatoes
       </a>
       , the film has an approval rating of 98% based on 305 reviews, with an average rating of 8.87/10. The site's critical consensus reads, "Deftly blending comedy, adventure, and honest emotion,
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       is a rare second sequel that really works."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-rt_4-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-rt-4">
         [4]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       was the best-reviewed film of 2010 on Rotten Tomatoes.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-121">
        <a href="#cite_note-121">
         [121]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Metacritic" title="Metacritic">
        Metacritic
       </a>
       , another review aggregator which assigns a
       <a href="/wiki/Normalization_(statistics)" title="Normalization (statistics)">
        normalized
       </a>
       rating to reviews, gave the film a score of 92 out of 100 based on 39 critics, indicating "universal acclaim."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-mc_5-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-mc-5">
         [5]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Time_(magazine)" title="Time (magazine)">
         TIME
        </a>
       </i>
       named
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       the "best film of 2010,"
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-122">
        <a href="#cite_note-122">
         [122]
        </a>
       </sup>
       as did
       <a href="/wiki/Quentin_Tarantino" title="Quentin Tarantino">
        Quentin Tarantino
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-nordyke1_123-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-nordyke1-123">
         [123]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In 2011,
       <i>
        TIME
       </i>
       named it one of "The 25 All-TIME Best Animated Films."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-124">
        <a href="#cite_note-124">
         [124]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Audiences polled by
       <a href="/wiki/CinemaScore" title="CinemaScore">
        CinemaScore
       </a>
       gave the film an average grade of "A" on an A+ to F scale, the same score as the
       <a href="/wiki/Toy_Story" title="Toy Story">
        first film
       </a>
       , but down from the "A+" earned by the
       <a href="/wiki/Toy_Story_2" title="Toy Story 2">
        second film
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-125">
        <a href="#cite_note-125">
         [125]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <div class="thumb tright">
       <div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;">
        <a class="image" href="/wiki/File:Quentin_Tarantino_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg">
         <img alt="" class="thumbimage" data-file-height="3016" data-file-width="2256" decoding="async" height="227" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0b/Quentin_Tarantino_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg/170px-Quentin_Tarantino_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0b/Quentin_Tarantino_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg/255px-Quentin_Tarantino_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0b/Quentin_Tarantino_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg/340px-Quentin_Tarantino_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg 2x" width="170"/>
        </a>
        <div class="thumbcaption">
         <div class="magnify">
          <a class="internal" href="/wiki/File:Quentin_Tarantino_by_Gage_Skidmore.jpg" title="Enlarge">
          </a>
         </div>
         <a href="/wiki/Quentin_Tarantino" title="Quentin Tarantino">
          Quentin Tarantino
         </a>
         placed the film at the top position in his list of favorite films of 2010.
         <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-nordyke1_123-1">
          <a href="#cite_note-nordyke1-123">
           [123]
          </a>
         </sup>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/A._O._Scott" title="A. O. Scott">
        A. O. Scott
       </a>
       of
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_New_York_Times" title="The New York Times">
         The New York Times
        </a>
       </i>
       stated "This filmthis whole three-part, 15-year epicabout the adventures of a bunch of silly plastic junk turns out also to be a long, melancholy meditation on loss, impermanence and that noble, stubborn, foolish thing called love."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-126">
        <a href="#cite_note-126">
         [126]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Owen_Gleiberman" title="Owen Gleiberman">
        Owen Gleiberman
       </a>
       from
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Entertainment_Weekly" title="Entertainment Weekly">
         Entertainment Weekly
        </a>
       </i>
       gave the film an "A" saying "Even with the bar raised high,
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       enchanted and moved me so deeply I was flabbergasted that a digitally animated comedy about plastic playthings could have this effect."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-127">
        <a href="#cite_note-127">
         [127]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Gleiberman also wrote in the next issue that he, along with many other grown men, cried at the end of the film.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-128">
        <a href="#cite_note-128">
         [128]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Michael Rechtshaffen of
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Hollywood_Reporter" title="The Hollywood Reporter">
         The Hollywood Reporter
        </a>
       </i>
       also gave the film a positive review, saying "Woody, Buzz and playmates make a thoroughly engaging, emotionally satisfying return."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-129">
        <a href="#cite_note-129">
         [129]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Mark_Kermode" title="Mark Kermode">
        Mark Kermode
       </a>
       of the
       <a href="/wiki/BBC" title="BBC">
        BBC
       </a>
       gave the film, and the series, a glowing review, calling it "the best movie trilogy of all time."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-130">
        <a href="#cite_note-130">
         [130]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/USA_Today" title="USA Today">
         USA Today
        </a>
       </i>
       , Claudia Puig gave the film a complete 4-
       <a href="/wiki/Star_(classification)" title="Star (classification)">
        star rating
       </a>
       , writing "This installment, the best of the three, is everything a movie should be: hilarious, touching, exciting, and clever."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-131">
        <a href="#cite_note-131">
         [131]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Lou_Lumenick" title="Lou Lumenick">
        Lou Lumenick
       </a>
       of the
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/New_York_Post" title="New York Post">
         New York Post
        </a>
       </i>
       wrote "
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       (which is pointlessly being shown in 3-D at most locations) may not be a masterpiece, but it still had me in tears at the end."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-132">
        <a href="#cite_note-132">
         [132]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Michael_Phillips_(critic)" title="Michael Phillips (critic)">
        Michael Phillips
       </a>
       of the
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Chicago_Tribune" title="Chicago Tribune">
         Chicago Tribune
        </a>
       </i>
       gave the film 3 out of 4 stars, writing that "Compared with the riches of all kinds in recent Pixar masterworks such as
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Ratatouille_(film)" title="Ratatouille (film)">
         Ratatouille
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/WALL-E" title="WALL-E">
         WALL-E
        </a>
       </i>
       , and
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Up_(2009_film)" title="Up (2009 film)">
         Up
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       looks and plays like an exceptionally slick and confident product, as opposed to a magical blend of commerce and popular art."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-133">
        <a href="#cite_note-133">
         [133]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Roger Moore of the
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Orlando_Sentinel" title="Orlando Sentinel">
         Orlando Sentinel
        </a>
       </i>
       , who gave the film 3 out of 4 stars, wrote "Dazzling, scary, and sentimental,
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       is a dark and emotional conclusion to the film series that made Pixar famous."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-134">
        <a href="#cite_note-134">
         [134]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       <a href="/wiki/Cahiers_du_Cin%C3%A9ma" title="Cahiers du Cinma">
        Cahiers du Cinma
       </a>
       put it at the fourth place of
       <a href="/wiki/Cahiers_du_Cin%C3%A9ma%27s_Annual_Top_10_Lists" title="Cahiers du Cinma's Annual Top 10 Lists">
        its top ten
       </a>
       best
       <a href="/wiki/2010_in_film" title="2010 in film">
        2010 films
       </a>
       .
      </p>
      <p>
       In 2018,
       <a href="/wiki/IndieWire" title="IndieWire">
        IndieWire
       </a>
       writers ranked the script the 10th best American screenplay of the 21st century.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-135">
        <a href="#cite_note-135">
         [135]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Accolades">
        Accolades
       </span>
      </h3>
      <p>
       On January 25, 2011, the
       <a href="/wiki/Academy_of_Motion_Picture_Arts_and_Sciences" title="Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences">
        Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences
       </a>
       announced that
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       was not only nominated for
       <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Animated_Feature" title="Academy Award for Best Animated Feature">
        Best Animated Feature
       </a>
       , but also for
       <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Picture" title="Academy Award for Best Picture">
        Best Picture
       </a>
       . This makes
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       not only the first animated sequel in history to be nominated for Best Picture, but also just the third animated film to ever be so nominated (following
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Beauty_and_the_Beast_(1991_film)" title="Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)">
         Beauty and the Beast
        </a>
       </i>
       and
       <i>
        Up
       </i>
       ), with
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       becoming the second Pixar film to be nominated for both awards.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-136">
        <a href="#cite_note-136">
         [136]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       also became the first-ever Pixar filmand the first animated feature film since
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Shrek" title="Shrek">
         Shrek
        </a>
       </i>
       to be nominated for the
       <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Adapted_Screenplay" title="Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay">
        Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-137">
        <a href="#cite_note-137">
         [137]
        </a>
       </sup>
       though six of Pixar's previous films were nominated for the
       <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Original_Screenplay" title="Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay">
        Best Original Screenplay
       </a>
       :
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Toy_Story" title="Toy Story">
         Toy Story
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-LATWalleScreenplay_138-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-LATWalleScreenplay-138">
         [138]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <i>
        Finding Nemo
       </i>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-LATWalleScreenplay_138-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-LATWalleScreenplay-138">
         [138]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Incredibles" title="The Incredibles">
         The Incredibles
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-LATWalleScreenplay_138-2">
        <a href="#cite_note-LATWalleScreenplay-138">
         [138]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <i>
        Ratatouille
       </i>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-LATWalleScreenplay_138-3">
        <a href="#cite_note-LATWalleScreenplay-138">
         [138]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <i>
        WALL-E
       </i>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-LATWalleScreenplay_138-4">
        <a href="#cite_note-LATWalleScreenplay-138">
         [138]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and
       <i>
        Up
       </i>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-139">
        <a href="#cite_note-139">
         [139]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In 2011, it was nominated for a
       <a href="/wiki/Nickelodeon_Kids%27_Choice_Awards" title="Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Awards">
        Kids' Choice Award
       </a>
       for Favorite Animated Movie, but lost to
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Despicable_Me_(film)" title="Despicable Me (film)">
         Despicable Me
        </a>
       </i>
       .
      </p>

          Jason Johnston, Eric Froemling, David Ryu, JD Northrup
         </td>
        </tr>
       </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Film_score" title="Film score">
        film score
       </a>
       for
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       was composed and conducted by
       <a href="/wiki/Randy_Newman" title="Randy Newman">
        Randy Newman
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-BFI_9-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-BFI-9">
         [9]
        </a>
       </sup>
       his sixth for Pixar after
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Toy_Story" title="Toy Story">
         Toy Story
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/A_Bug%27s_Life" title="A Bug's Life">
         A Bug's Life
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Toy_Story_2" title="Toy Story 2">
         Toy Story 2
        </a>
       </i>
       ,
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Monsters,_Inc." title="Monsters, Inc.">
         Monsters, Inc.
        </a>
       </i>
       , and
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Cars_(film)" title="Cars (film)">
         Cars
        </a>
       </i>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-162">
        <a href="#cite_note-162">
         [162]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Initially, Disney released the soundtrack only as
       <a href="/wiki/Music_download" title="Music download">
        digital download
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-AboutSoundtrack_161-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-AboutSoundtrack-161">
         [161]
        </a>
       </sup>
       This was the second instance where Disney did not release the award-winning soundtrack of a Pixar film on
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/CD" title="CD">
        CD
       </a>
       , the first being
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Up_(2009_film)" title="Up (2009 film)">
         Up
        </a>
       </i>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-163">
        <a href="#cite_note-163">
         [163]
        </a>
       </sup>
       In January 2012,
       <a href="/wiki/Intrada_Records" title="Intrada Records">
        Intrada
       </a>
       released the
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       soundtrack on CD.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-164">
        <a href="#cite_note-164">
         [164]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       All tracks are written by
       <a href="/wiki/Randy_Newman" title="Randy Newman">
        Randy Newman
       </a>
       .
      </p>

      <p>
       In addition to the tracks included in the soundtrack album, the film also uses several other tracks such as "
       <a href="/wiki/Dream_Weaver" title="Dream Weaver">
        Dream Weaver
       </a>
       " by
       <a href="/wiki/Gary_Wright" title="Gary Wright">
        Gary Wright
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-165">
        <a href="#cite_note-165">
         [165]
        </a>
       </sup>
       "
       <a href="/wiki/Le_Freak" title="Le Freak">
        Le Freak
       </a>
       " by
       <a href="/wiki/Chic_(band)" title="Chic (band)">
        Chic
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-iTunesSongbook_166-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-iTunesSongbook-166">
         [166]
        </a>
       </sup>
       and Randy Newman's original version of "
       <a href="/wiki/You%27ve_Got_a_Friend_in_Me" title="You've Got a Friend in Me">
        You've Got a Friend in Me
       </a>
       ."
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-iTunesSongbook_166-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-iTunesSongbook-166">
         [166]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Furthermore, tracks "Cowboy!" and "Come to Papa" included material from Newman's rejected score to
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Air_Force_One_(film)" title="Air Force One (film)">
         Air Force One
        </a>
       </i>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-Air_Force_One_167-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-Air_Force_One-167">
         [167]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The song "Losing You" from Newman's own album
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Harps_and_Angels" title="Harps and Angels">
         Harps and Angels
        </a>
       </i>
       was also used in the first trailer for the film.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-168">
        <a href="#cite_note-168">
         [168]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The
       <a href="/wiki/Judas_Priest" title="Judas Priest">
        Judas Priest
       </a>
       song "
       <a href="/wiki/Electric_Eye_(song)" title="Electric Eye (song)">
        Electric Eye
       </a>
       " was also used in the film in the temp score for the opening scene of
       <i>
        Toy Story 3
       </i>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-169">
        <a href="#cite_note-169">
         [169]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The aliens are playing the tune in their sports car. The song was ultimately replaced by Newman's score.
      </p>

      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Sequel">
        Sequel
       </span>
      </h2>
      <p>
       <span class="anchor" id="Sequels">
       </span>
       <span class="anchor" id="Sequel">
       </span>
       <span class="anchor" id="Potential_sequel">
       </span>
      </p>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       Main article:
       <a href="/wiki/Toy_Story_4" title="Toy Story 4">
        Toy Story 4
       </a>
      </div>
      <p>
       The sequel, titled
       <i>
        Toy Story 4
       </i>
       , was released on June 21, 2019,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-THRTS4Incr2_173-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-THRTS4Incr2-173">
         [173]
        </a>
       </sup>
       with most of the main cast returning for the film.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-174">
        <a href="#cite_note-174">
         [174]
        </a>
       </sup>
       The film was originally to be directed by
       <a href="/wiki/John_Lasseter" title="John Lasseter">
        John Lasseter
       </a>
       and co-directed by
       <a href="/wiki/Josh_Cooley" title="Josh Cooley">
        Josh Cooley
       </a>
       ,
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-175">
        <a href="#cite_note-175">
         [175]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-176">
        <a href="#cite_note-176">
         [176]
        </a>
       </sup>
       but in July 2017 Cooley was confirmed as the sole director.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-177">
        <a href="#cite_note-177">
         [177]
        </a>
       </sup>
       <a href="/wiki/Don_Rickles" title="Don Rickles">
        Don Rickles
       </a>
       had signed on to return to voice
       <a href="/wiki/Mr._Potato_Head" title="Mr. Potato Head">
        Mr. Potato Head
       </a>
       , but died before any lines could be recorded.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-178">
        <a href="#cite_note-178">
         [178]
        </a>
       </sup>
       Cooley later confirmed that archived recordings of Rickles would be used instead.
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-RicklesVoice_179-0">
        <a href="#cite_note-RicklesVoice-179">
         [179]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>

# find info on tr rows and use a loop to iterate through tr

info_rows = infobox.find_all('tr')
for row in info_rows:
    print(row.prettify())

#a function to breakdown content_value
def get_content_value(row_data):
    if row_data.find('li'):
        return[li.get_text(' ',strip=True).replace(u'\xa0',' ')for li in row_data.find_all('li')]
    else:
        return row_data.get_text(' ',strip=True).replace(u'\xa0',' ')
    

movie_info = {}    

for index, row in enumerate(info_rows):
    if index == 0:
        movie_info['title'] = row.find('th').get_text(' ',strip=True)
    elif index == 1:
        continue
    else:
        content_key = row.find('th').get_text(' ',strip=True)
        content_value = get_content_value(row.find('td'))
        movie_info[content_key] = content_value
        
        
movie_info

   <h1 class="firstHeading" id="firstHeading">
    List of Walt Disney Pictures films
   </h1>
   <div class="mw-body-content" id="bodyContent">
    <div class="noprint" id="siteSub">
     From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
    </div>
    <div id="contentSub">
    </div>
    <div id="contentSub2">
    </div>
    <div id="jump-to-nav">
    </div>
    <a class="mw-jump-link" href="#mw-head">
     Jump to navigation
    </a>
    <a class="mw-jump-link" href="#searchInput">
     Jump to search
    </a>
    <div class="mw-content-ltr" dir="ltr" id="mw-content-text" lang="en">
     <div class="mw-parser-output">
      <div class="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">
       Wikipedia list article
      </div>
      <div class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" role="note">
       "List of Disney films" redirects here. For a broader list of Disney films, see
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/List_of_Walt_Disney_Studios_films" title="List of Walt Disney Studios films">
        List of Walt Disney Studios films
       </a>
       .
      </div>
      <p>
       This is a
       <b>
        list of films
       </b>
       produced by and released under the
       <b>
        <a href="/wiki/Walt_Disney_Pictures" title="Walt Disney Pictures">
         Walt Disney Pictures
        </a>
       </b>
       banner (known as that since 1983, with
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/Never_Cry_Wolf_(film)" title="Never Cry Wolf (film)">
         Never Cry Wolf
        </a>
       </i>
       as its first release) and films released before that under the former name of the
       <a href="/wiki/Parent_company" title="Parent company">
        parent company
       </a>
       ,
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Walt_Disney_Productions" title="Walt Disney Productions">
        Walt Disney Productions
       </a>
       (19291983). Most films listed here were distributed theatrically in the United States by the company's distribution division,
       <a href="/wiki/Walt_Disney_Studios_Motion_Pictures" title="Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures">
        Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures
       </a>
       (formerly known as Buena Vista Distribution Company [19531987] and Buena Vista Pictures Distribution [19872007]). The Disney features produced before
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/The_Living_Desert" title="The Living Desert">
         The Living Desert
        </a>
       </i>
       (1953) were originally distributed by
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/RKO_Radio_Pictures" title="RKO Radio Pictures">
        RKO Radio Pictures
       </a>
       , and are now distributed by Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures. Some films produced by Walt Disney Pictures are also released through the parent company's streaming service,
       <a href="/wiki/Disney%2B" title="Disney+">
        Disney+
       </a>
       .
       <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1">
        <a href="#cite_note-1">
         [1]
        </a>
       </sup>
      </p>
      <p>
       This list is organized by release date and includes live-action feature films (including theatrical and
       <a href="/wiki/Disney%2B" title="Disney+">
        streaming releases
       </a>
       ), animated feature films (including films developed and produced by
       <a href="/wiki/Walt_Disney_Animation_Studios" title="Walt Disney Animation Studios">
        Walt Disney Animation Studios
       </a>
       and
       <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Pixar_Animation_Studios" title="Pixar Animation Studios">
        Pixar Animation Studios
       </a>
       ), and documentary films (including titles from the
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/True-Life_Adventures" title="True-Life Adventures">
         True-Life Adventures
        </a>
       </i>
       series and films produced by the
       <a href="/wiki/Disneynature" title="Disneynature">
        Disneynature
       </a>
       label). For an exclusive list of animated films released by Walt Disney Pictures and its previous entities see
       <i>
        <a href="/wiki/List_of_Disney_theatrical_animated_feature_films" title="List of Disney theatrical animated feature films">
         List of Disney theatrical animated feature films
        </a>
       </i>
       .
      </p>
      <p>
       This list is only for films released under the main Disney banner. The list does not include films produced or released by other existing, defunct or divested labels or subsidiaries owned by
       <a href="/wiki/Walt_Disney_Studios_(division)" title="Walt Disney Studios (division)">
        Walt Disney Studios
       </a>
       (i.e.
       <a href="/wiki/Marvel_Studios" title="Marvel Studios">
        Marvel Studios
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Lucasfilm" title="Lucasfilm">
        Lucasfilm
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/20th_Century_Studios" title="20th Century Studios">
        20th Century Studios
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Searchlight_Pictures" title="Searchlight Pictures">
        Searchlight Pictures
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Fox_2000_Pictures" title="Fox 2000 Pictures">
        Fox 2000 Pictures
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Touchstone_Pictures" title="Touchstone Pictures">
        Touchstone Pictures
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Hollywood_Pictures" title="Hollywood Pictures">
        Hollywood Pictures
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/National_Geographic_Society" title="National Geographic Society">
        National Geographic Documentary Films
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Miramax" title="Miramax">
        Miramax Films
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/Dimension_Films" title="Dimension Films">
        Dimension Films
       </a>
       ,
       <a href="/wiki/ESPN_Films" title="ESPN Films">
        ESPN Films
       </a>
       etc.; unless they are credited as co-production partners) nor any direct-to-video releases, TV films, theatrical re-releases, or films originally released by other non-Disney studios.
      </p>
      <div aria-labelledby="mw-toc-heading" class="toc" id="toc" role="navigation">
       <input class="toctogglecheckbox" id="toctogglecheckbox" role="button" style="display:none" type="checkbox"/>

      <h3>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="2020s">
        2020s
       </span>
      </h3>
      <p>
       All films listed are
       <a href="/wiki/Art_release" title="Art release">
        theatrical releases
       </a>
       unless specified. Films labeled with a
       <b>
        
       </b>
       symbol signifies a
       <a href="/wiki/Streaming_media" title="Streaming media">
        streaming release
       </a>
       exclusively through
       <a href="/wiki/Disney%2B" title="Disney+">
        Disney+
       </a>
       ; a
       <b>
        
       </b>
       symbol signifies a
       <a href="/wiki/Video_on_demand#Premium" title="Video on demand">
        premium video on demand
       </a>
       release through Disney+ and
       <a href="/wiki/Limited_theatrical_release" title="Limited theatrical release">
        limited theatrical release
       </a>
       .
      </p>

      <h2>
       <span class="mw-headline" id="Upcoming">
        Upcoming
       </span>
      </h2>
      <p>
       All films listed are
       <a href="/wiki/Art_release" title="Art release">
        theatrical releases
       </a>
       unless specified. Films labeled with a
       <b>
        
       </b>
       symbol signifies a
       <a href="/wiki/Streaming_media" title="Streaming media">
        streaming release
       </a>
       exclusively through
       <a href="/wiki/Disney%2B" title="Disney+">
        Disney+
       </a>
       ; a
       <b>
        
       </b>
       symbol signifies a
       <a href="/wiki/Video_on_demand#Premium" title="Video on demand">
        premium video on demand
       </a>
       release through Disney+ and
       <a href="/wiki/Limited_theatrical_release" title="Limited theatrical release">
        limited theatrical release
       </a>
       ; a  symbol signifies a
       <a href="/wiki/Simultaneous_release" title="Simultaneous release">
        simultaneous release
       </a>
       to theatres and on premium video on demand.
      </p>
